column11: cdt@sanger.ac.uk cs4@sanger.ac.uk da1@sanger.ac.uk ea5@sanger.ac.uk hr6@sanger.ac.uk lm5@sanger.ac.uk vo1@sanger.ac.uk
column46: The aim of the project is to determine whether exposure of honey bees to environmental compounds leads to DNA mutations through sequencing. %0D%0ABees were dosed with a panel of 7 compounds (Azoxystobin%2C Chlorothalnil%2C Clothianidin%2C Lambda cyhalothrin%2C Fluvalinate%2C Prochoraz or Dimethoate). Dosing was carried out by applying the compound (diluted in either Acetone or Triton-X-100) to the thorax of the bee. Un-dosed bees were also collected along with vehicle controls.
column48: The Bee Genomic Evidence of Novel Environmental Signatures%3A BEE-GEnES project (Nanoseq)
column51: The Bee Genomic Evidence of Novel Environmental Signatures%3A BEE-GEnES project (Nanoseq)

column46: The aim of the project is to determine whether exposure of honey bees to environmental compounds leads to DNA mutations through sequencing. %0D%0ABees were dosed with a panel of 7 compounds (Azoxystobin%2C Chlorothalnil%2C Clothianidin%2C Lambda cyhalothrin%2C Fluvalinate%2C Prochoraz or Dimethoate). column46: The aim of the project is to determine whether exposure of honey bees to environmental compounds leads to DNA mutations through sequencing. %0D%0ABees were dosed with a panel of 7 compounds (Azoxystobin%2C Chlorothalnil%2C Clothianidin%2C Lambda cyhalothrin%2C Fluvalinate%2C Prochoraz or Dimethoate).
